{{distinguish|canzone}}{{Refimprove|date=April 2012}}

The '''''canzona''''' (It. plural '''''canzone''''') is an instrumental musical form of the 16th and 17th centuries that developed from the Netherlandish [[chanson]] {{harv|Caldwell|2001}}. It differed from the similar forms of [[ricercare]] and [[Fantasia (music)|fantasia]] in its livelier, markedly rhythmic material and separation into distinct sections {{harv|Grout|1960|loc=299}}.

At first based on Franco-Flemish [[polyphonic]] songs (chansons), later independently composed, the instrumental canzonas, such as the brass canzonas of [[Giovanni Gabrieli]] and the keyboard canzonas of [[Girolamo Frescobaldi]], influenced the [[fugue]],{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}} and the ensemble canzonas were the direct ancestors of the 17th-century ''[[sonata da chiesa]]'' {{harv|Grout|1960|loc=252}}. In Italian, ''canzona'' literally means "song".

