{{For|Emney's father, the comedian|Fred Emney Sr}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Use British English|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Fred Emney | image = Fred_Emney.jpg | birth_name = Frederick Arthur Round Emney | birth_date = {{Birth date|1900|02|12|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Prescot]], [[Lancashire]], [[England]], UK | death_date = {{Death date and age|1980|12|25|1900|02|12|df=y}} | death_place = [[Bognor Regis]], [[Sussex]], England, UK | occupation = Actor | years_active = | spouse = Hazel Wiles | website = }} '''Frederick Arthur Round Emney''' (12 February 1900 &ndash; 25 December 1980) was an English [[character actor]] and [[comedian]].<ref name=bfi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b9f1158ba|title=Fred Emney|publisher=}}</ref>
Emney was born in [[Prescot]], [[Lancashire]],<ref name="birth">GRO Register of Births Mar 1900 Frederick Arthur R Emney 8b 725 PRESCOT</ref><ref name="census1901">1901 Census: RG13/500 f.123 p.3 Fred Arthur Emney aged 1 living in Camberwell, but born Liverpool, Lancashire</ref> the son of Blanche (née Round) and [[Fred Emney Sr|Fred Emney]], a [[music hall]] entertainer.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803095749904|title=Fred Emney - Oxford Reference|publisher=}}</ref> His great-uncle was the actor [[Arthur Williams (actor)|Arthur Williams]]. Emney junior grew up in London and was educated at [[Cranleigh School]].<ref name=cranleigh/>
He made his film debut in 1935, having previously worked in [[music hall]].<ref name=bfi/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/fred-emney-p21835|title=Fred Emney - Biography, Movie Highlights and Photos - AllMovie|website=AllMovie}}</ref> He became a familiar figure to screen audiences, usually playing the "posh fat [[:wikt:bloke|bloke]]", usually gruff and invariably wearing a [[monocle]].<ref name=cranleigh>{{cite web|url=https://1865.cranleigh.org/fred-emney/|title=Fred Emney - Cranleigh School 1865|website=1865.cranleigh.org}}</ref> During the 1950s, he had his own television show which featured sketches and deft piano pieces often composed by him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CJTfeICgTtMC&pg=PA63&lpg=PA63&dq=the+fred+emney+show+bbc&source=bl&ots=UF3KkzVngH&sig=OlFG0cEIFTC5hOhzWLpoDrcogWI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTnMH19ebWAhWjJcAKHZ6xCOYQ6AEIUzAI#v=onepage&q=the+fred+emney+show+bbc&f=false|title=Ronnie Barker: The Authorized Biography|first=Bob|last=McCabe|date=26 May 2005|publisher=BBC Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> Some were released on record.<ref>''Fred Emney'' an extended play released on UK Decca (DFE 6554) in 1958</ref> He had a short spell as straight man to puppets [[Pinky and Perky]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forthechildren.org.uk/details.asp?pid=204|title=For the Children: Children's Television in the UK|website=www.forthechildren.org.uk}}</ref>
His sister Joan Emney was an actress who sometimes appeared with him in the same stage productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theatricalia.com/play/37n/the-flying-trapeze/production/79f|title=Production of The Flying Trapeze - Theatricalia|website=theatricalia.com}}</ref>
Fred Emney died in [[Bognor Regis]], [[Sussex]] on [[Christmas Day]] 1980.<ref>GRO Register of Deaths: DEC 1980 18 1714 CHICHESTER - Frederick Patrick R. Emney, DoB = 12 Feb 1900</ref>
